WEBVTT

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:07.000
All right. Okay. I'm Winston Chang, and I'm going to be talking about the R6 Class System.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:16.000
So, first off, I want to... one of my colleagues pointed me to this webpage. This is at r-documentation.org, run by Datacamp,

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:24.000
and it lists the most downloaded packages. And I didn't realize this, but apparently R6 is the most downloaded package.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
It's for object-oriented programming. And so that was a little surprising to me.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:37.000
But when I thought about it, it made sense because there's a lot of very popular packages that use R6, like dplyr, for example.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:45.000
One thing I did find very surprising, though, was that in this column here, it apparently is the most popular directly downloaded package,

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
which means that a lot of people are doing install.package as R6.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
So, either people are very, very into object-oriented programming in R, or there's some problem with the data.

00:00:56.000 --> 00:00:57.000
And I see...

00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Okay, so they're still working on this at Datacamp. So, this is not true, sadly. As I suspected.

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:15.000
All right, so I'm just going to give you some numbers here, R6 by the numbers.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:20.000
It's been out on CRAN for three years. It's only 588 lines of code.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:24.000
There's about 1,700 lines of tests, so it's a well-tested package.

00:01:24.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Apparently, it's the number one package on CRAN, at least for indirect downloads. I hope that's true.

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
And I've given zero talks about it until today, so I'm very excited.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:39.000
This is my first talk about R6, even though it's been out for a while and is widely used.

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:44.000
So, I'm going to start off with talking about R's built-in object-oriented programming systems.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:49.000
There's a classification that John Chambers uses in his book, Extending R.

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:55.000
Functional object-oriented programming systems and encapsulated object-oriented programming systems.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:02.000
So, for the functional object-oriented programming, that's exemplified by the S3 and S4 systems in R.

00:02:02.000 --> 00:02:10.000
And for encapsulated object-oriented programming, that's exemplified by reference classes in R.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And these are the ones that are built into R.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:15.000
So, the differences between them include this.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:20.000
For functional object-oriented programming, the objects contain data,

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
but class methods that operate on those objects, they're separate.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
The methods themselves are separate from the objects, and the objects are not mutable.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
So, whenever you have a function that operates on an object, and if it modifies the object,

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:43.000
what actually happens is you get a copy of the object, and then you can choose to store that modified copy or not.

00:02:43.000 --> 00:02:49.000
For encapsulated object-oriented programming, the objects contain both the data and the methods.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:55.000
The objects are mutable. They can change when you call a method or if you modify things in it.

00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:58.000
And it's also known as classical object-oriented programming.

00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:04.000
So, this is the type of system you'd see with Java, C++, or Python.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:09.000
This is much more common in the wider programming world.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Okay, so for using functional object-oriented programming, you might do something like,

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
if you've got your object X, you'd call summary of X, and there might be a method for your particular class that gives you a summary.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
If you want to modify X, you'd call some function, modify, here, modifyX.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.000
As I said, that doesn't modify X in place. It returns a new object, which you would have to save back in X.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:41.000
Now, for encapsulated object-oriented programming, the methods are part of the object.

00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:45.000
The dollar sign is the subset operator, so you'd say X$summary.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:48.000
You might have a method that modifies the object to X$modify.

00:03:48.000 --> 00:03:52.000
That could change X in place. You don't have to save that back in X.

00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:00.000
If you pass X to a function, like I have this object called trim, it may change X, or it might not change X.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:03.000
So, from the outside, you can't tell.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Because of this, it can be easier to reason about functional object-oriented programming,

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:14.000
where every time you want to modify an object, you always have an assignment operator.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Whereas with encapsulated, you don't know if it's going to change.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:24.000
But encapsulated object-oriented programming is useful for representing data that evolves over time.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:32.000
Some real-world examples of this, where R6 is used, are Shiny.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
Their Shiny session is represented with an R6 object.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:39.000
It represents the state of the application as the user interacts with it.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:44.000
In dplyr, R6 objects are used to represent database connections.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:54.000
In a relatively new package called ProcessX by Gabor, R6 objects are used to represent system processes.

00:04:54.000 --> 00:04:58.000
In this case, these are all things that have connections to things that are outside of R.

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:04.000
This is one very common use case for encapsulated object-oriented programming.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.000
Here's a basic R6 class.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:12.000
This is how you define a class.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.000
You call function R6 class.

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You give it a label. In this case, it's accumulator, or a name.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:27.000
Then here, I say there's a list of these public properties.

00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:29.000
One of them is the sum.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:33.000
This accumulator, I just want to add values to a total sum.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
The sum starts off at zero.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:37.000
Then there's a method called add.

00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.000
This is a function that takes a value x.

00:05:42.000 --> 00:05:48.000
It takes self$sum, adds x, and then assigns it back to self$sum.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:51.000
Then this method returns self.

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.000
It returns the accumulator object so that you can chain it together.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:57.000
We'll see this below.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:00.000
That defines the class.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.000
To instantiate the class, to create an object of that class,

00:06:03.000 --> 00:06:08.000
you'd say accumulator$new, and save that in x.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:15.000
Now I can say x$add4, or x$add10, and then add10,

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:20.000
because this first add10 returns that accumulator object,

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:26.000
so I can keep using the dollar sign and calling this add method.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:30.000
At the end, I can access the sum just by using x$sum.

00:06:30.000 --> 00:06:34.000
That's the very basics of creating an R6 class.

00:06:35.000 --> 00:06:39.000
For an example that's a little bit more useful,

00:06:39.000 --> 00:06:41.000
here's an example of a stack.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:45.000
In Shiny, we use stacks to keep track of various things,

00:06:45.000 --> 00:06:48.000
keep track of various bits of state.

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:50.000
I won't go into the details of this code,

00:06:50.000 --> 00:06:53.000
but the important things are that there's some public methods here.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:55.000
Push, you push things on the stack.

00:06:55.000 --> 00:06:58.000
Pop, you take the top item off the stack.

00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:02.000
Size is a method that tells you how many items are in the stack.

00:07:03.000 --> 00:07:08.000
Now the new thing here is that there's also some private stuff.

00:07:08.000 --> 00:07:10.000
This is a list.

00:07:10.000 --> 00:07:13.000
It contains one thing, the items in the stack,

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:17.000
which also begins as an empty list.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:20.000
They're not accessible from outside.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:26.000
From inside the class, you can use private$items to access that value,

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:30.000
so I can modify it or read it using private$items.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:31.000
This keeps it encapsulated.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:35.000
All you get to see are the functions from the outside.

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:40.000
To use it, you'd say s is stack$new, s$push1,

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:43.000
push5 through 10, pushtext,

00:07:43.000 --> 00:07:45.000
and then if you pop them off,

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:48.000
it'll take them off in reverse order.

00:07:48.000 --> 00:07:52.000
That's a slightly more useful example of a class.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:07:58.000
If you were to do this with functional programming,

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.000
you might have a function stack that creates a stack object

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:03.000
and you save it in s.

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:04.000
Then when you want to add things to it,

00:08:04.000 --> 00:08:07.000
you'd have to say push s, 1,

00:08:07.000 --> 00:08:08.000
and that doesn't modify s in place,

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:11.000
so you have to save that back in s.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
Every time you push things, you'd have to do that.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.000
If you want to remove things from the stack,

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:20.000
if you want to get the top item and then remove it from the stack,

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:23.000
first you'd call a function that takes that top item off,

00:08:23.000 --> 00:08:26.000
let's say last of s.

00:08:26.000 --> 00:08:28.000
Save that in x1.

00:08:28.000 --> 00:08:31.000
Then you'd call removeLast of s to modify s itself,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:33.000
and then you'd have to save that back in s.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:35.000
There's two steps here.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Whereas if you're using R6,

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:39.000
the method, it both modifies s

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
and then it returns the value that you're interested in.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:52.000
Another handy feature of R6 classes are initializer methods.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:55.000
In the stack class, it just starts off empty.

00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:57.000
The one that I showed you,

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.000
but you can add a special method called initialize.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:06.000
In this one, it's a function that takes dot, dot, dot arguments

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:10.000
and it just assigns those elements as the beginning,

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:12.000
the starting state of the stack.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:15.000
If I say stack$new, I'd say stack$new 5, 6, 7,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:19.000
and then the stack starts with those items in the stack.

00:09:20.000 --> 00:09:24.000
It also supports inheritance.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:26.000
If you want to create a subclass,

00:09:26.000 --> 00:09:28.000
I've got my base class stack,

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:31.000
and then I want to create this fancier stack class

00:09:31.000 --> 00:09:34.000
called stack2 with some extra features.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:38.000
I'd say R6 class inherit equals stack.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:43.000
Then there's an initialize method.

00:09:43.000 --> 00:09:47.000
I can add methods and I can override methods.

00:09:47.000 --> 00:09:49.000
I can add a push method,

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:52.000
which overrides the base class's push method.

00:09:52.000 --> 00:09:56.000
In this one, it takes, again, a variable list of arguments

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:00.000
and it loops over them

00:10:00.000 --> 00:10:03.000
and it calls the superclass's push method

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:07.000
and just pushes each one onto the stack.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:11.000
You can use super to access methods from the superclass.

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:17.000
One nice thing, again, is that the API encapsulates the data,

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:19.000
so all you get to see from the outside,

00:10:19.000 --> 00:10:21.000
going back to the original stack class,

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:23.000
is just these methods.

00:10:23.000 --> 00:10:25.000
If you want to refactor it and make it more performant,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:27.000
make it more efficient,

00:10:27.000 --> 00:10:29.000
you just have to make sure those methods

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:31.000
continue to work properly.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:33.000
If you change the internal data structure,

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:35.000
you don't have to worry that somebody has written code

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:37.000
that uses that internal data structure

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:41.000
because it will break when you change it.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Now, when should you use R6?

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.000
When you need objects with reference semantics,

00:10:45.000 --> 00:10:47.000
that's often, again,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:49.000
when you're representing external resources,

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:51.000
that's a common case.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:53.000
When you want to encapsulate the data

00:10:53.000 --> 00:10:55.000
and just expose a particular interface to your data,

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:57.000
and also when you don't want to pollute

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.000
your working environment with a whole bunch of methods.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:03.000
Those methods, instead of just floating out there,

00:11:03.000 --> 00:11:05.000
they're part of your objects,

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:07.000
so they're contained in there.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
Reference classes existed before R6 did,

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
so a comparison between them.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:19.000
Some of the advantages of R6

00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.000
are that it's simple and it's lightweight.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
As I said, it's only 508 lines of code.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:25.000
It supports private properties,

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:27.000
whereas with reference classes,

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.000
everything is public.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:31.000
There's robust inheritance.

00:11:31.000 --> 00:11:33.000
You can have inheritance across packages

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:35.000
without any compromises,

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:37.000
and that can be a bit of a problem

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:39.000
for reference classes.

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:41.000
Also, the generators and the R6 objects

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:43.000
are fully encapsulated.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:45.000
Once you've created them,

00:11:45.000 --> 00:11:47.000
they don't call any functions from the R6 package,

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.000
which means that you can save them out

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:51.000
and then load them in another R session

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.000
which has, say, a different version of R6

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:55.000
or doesn't even have R6 installed at all,

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:57.000
and they will continue to function.

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:01.000
That can avoid a class

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:03.000
of sort of hard-to-diagnose bugs

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:05.000
because of that.

00:12:05.000 --> 00:12:07.000
For reference classes, it's built into R,

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:09.000
which is a big thing,

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:11.000
so there's built-in support everywhere.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:13.000
It's built using S4 and the methods package.

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:15.000
Also, the fields can have types

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.000
in reference classes.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:19.000
This is a comparison.

00:12:19.000 --> 00:12:21.000
Obviously, I'm biased.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:23.000
I'm sure somebody here will have something

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:25.000
to say about this.

00:12:25.000 --> 00:12:27.000
For more information,

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:29.000
you can see the vignettes.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:31.000
I think that's a pretty good introduction

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.000
if you go to the CRAN package page,

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.000
or you can just run the vignette function.

00:12:39.000 --> 00:12:41.000
How R6 is implemented.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
R6 objects are just environments

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:45.000
with a particular structure.

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
It's pretty simple

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:49.000
once you understand it.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:51.000
Normally, when you're

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:53.000
running R code, you have

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:55.000
your object here. This is just the value 10.

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.000
You have a binding

00:12:57.000 --> 00:12:59.000
to that object. This is the name

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:01.000
x, and it refers to this

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:03.000
object here, value 10.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:05.000
That binding lives in an environment.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:07.000
You're probably familiar

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:09.000
usually working in the global environment

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:11.000
if you're working at R at the console.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Environments have parents,

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
so that's what this arrow represents here,

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:17.000
that relationship. If it doesn't find

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
a binding here, it'll search in the parent

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:21.000
environment and it'll keep going until it hits the bottom.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:25.000
There's also function objects.

00:13:25.000 --> 00:13:27.000
They have

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
a special

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.000
thing, which is

00:13:31.000 --> 00:13:33.000
this arrow here represents the enclosing environment.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:35.000
That's sort of, in some sense,

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:37.000
the environment where the function runs.

00:13:37.000 --> 00:13:39.000
It'll search for things in this

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
enclosing environment.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.000
This is the basic

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:45.000
way that objects and binding environments

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:47.000
work.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
For R6,

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
an R6 object consists of usually two

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
or maybe three objects, or two

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
environments, I should say.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:57.000
One is the public-facing

00:13:57.000 --> 00:13:59.000
environment. I call it the public binding environment.

00:13:59.000 --> 00:14:01.000
It has x, and

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:03.000
this is a different function name from before.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:05.000
It's pow x y.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:09.000
This points to

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:11.000
a function, and this function's enclosing

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:13.000
environment is not this

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:15.000
public binding environment. It's a special enclosing environment

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:17.000
which contains just

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:19.000
the binding self.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:21.000
Self

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.000
refers back to this public binding environment.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:25.000
If you want to access x, you'd say

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:27.000
self$x.

00:14:27.000 --> 00:14:29.000
You can't just access x from that function

00:14:29.000 --> 00:14:31.000
directly.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:33.000
This enclosing environment,

00:14:33.000 --> 00:14:35.000
if you're in a package, it would typically be

00:14:35.000 --> 00:14:37.000
the package namespace.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:39.000
These functions can call all the

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
internal functions from that package.

00:14:43.000 --> 00:14:45.000
It looks like

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:47.000
I'm out of time.

00:14:47.000 --> 00:14:49.000
I'll just go back to

00:14:49.000 --> 00:14:51.000
the original slide. This is the basics

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:53.000
of how R6 is implemented.

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.000
There's two separate environments.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:57.000
I will go back to this,

00:14:57.000 --> 00:14:59.000
and I guess I can take some questions.

00:15:05.000 --> 00:15:07.000
Thanks,

00:15:07.000 --> 00:15:09.000
Winston. Questions?

00:15:15.000 --> 00:15:17.000
As you mentioned, the reference classes

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:19.000
seem very similar to classes implemented

